#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:23
# header
msgid "## The Carpentries Pedagogical Model"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:25
msgid "The Carpentries aims to teach computational competence to learners. We take an applied approach, avoiding the theoretical and general\n"
"in favor of the practical and specific. By showing learners how to solve specific problems with specific tools and providing hands-on\n"
"practice, we develop learners' confidence and lay the foundation for future learning."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:29
msgid "A critical component of this process is that learners are able to practice what they are learning in real time, get\n"
"feedback on what they are doing, and then apply those lessons learned to the next step in the learning process. Having\n"
"learners help each other during the workshops also helps to reinforce concepts taught during the workshops."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:33
msgid "A Carpentries workshop is an interactive event -- for learners and instructors. We give and\n"
"receive feedback throughout the course of a workshop. We incorporate assessments within the lesson materials and\n"
"ask for feedback on sticky notes during lunch breaks and at the end of each day. In this way, instructors can adjust the\n"
"pace and content of a workshop to meet the needs of the learners in that group, as well as collect feedback\n"
"that will help us improve lesson materials or methodology for future workshops. Instructors and helpers also provide\n"
"feedback to learners throughout workshops in order to get them unstuck or provide a greater depth of understanding about\n"
"the materials. Interacting in this way with the learners helps us determine how they are doing and figure out what concepts\n"
"people are having trouble with or where we might be able to move along more quickly."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:42
# header
msgid "## The Acquisition of Skill"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:44
msgid "Our approach is based on the work of researchers like Patricia Benner,\n"
"who applied the [Dreyfus model of skill acquisition][wikipedia-dreyfus-skill]\n"
"in her studies of\n"
"[how nurses progress from novice to expert](http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/0270467604265061)\n"
"([see also books by Benner](https://www.worldcat.org/search?q=au%3ABenner%2C+Patricia+E.&qt=hot_author)). This work indicates that\n"
"through practice and formal instruction, learners acquire skills and advance through distinct stages. In simplified form,\n"
"the three stages of this model are:"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:52
msgid "![Novice, Competent Practitioner, Expert](../fig/skill-level.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:54
# unordered list
msgid "*   *Novice*: someone who doesn't know what they don't know, i.e.,"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:55
msgid "    they don't yet know what the key ideas in the domain are or how they relate.\n"
"    One sign that someone is a novice is that their questions \"aren't even wrong\"."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:58
msgid "    > Example: A *novice* learner in a Carpentries workshop might never have heard of the bash shell, and therefore\n"
"    may have no understanding of how it relates to their file system or other programs on their computer."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:61
# unordered list
msgid "*   *Competent practitioner*: someone who has enough understanding for everyday purposes. They won't know all the details"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:62
msgid "of how something works and their understanding may not be entirely accurate, but it is sufficient for completing normal\n"
"tasks with normal effort under normal circumstances."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:65
msgid "    > Example: A *competent practitioner* in a Carpentries workshop might have used the shell before and understand how to\n"
"    move around directories and use individual programs, but they might not understand how they can fit these programs\n"
"    together to build scripts and automate large tasks."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:69
# unordered list
msgid "*   *Expert*: someone who can easily handle situations that are out of the ordinary."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:71
msgid "    > Example: An *expert* in a Carpentries workshop may have experience writing and running shell scripts and, when\n"
"    presented with a problem, immediately sees how these skills can be used to solve the problem."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:74
msgid "For now, we are primarily concerned with novices,\n"
"as this tends to characterize the Carpentries audience. (We, as instructors,\n"
"  are more likely to be competent practitioners or experts, and we'll\n"
"discuss this in a later section).  We'll next use an additional concept\n"
"to help us differentiate between novices and competent practitioners, which will have\n"
"implications for how we teach novices."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:81
# header
msgid "## Cognitive Development and Mental Models"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:83
msgid "Effective learning is facilitated by the creation of a well-founded mental model. A mental model is a collection of concepts and facts,\n"
"along with the relationships between those concepts, which a person has about a topic. For example, a long-time resident of the United\n"
"States may have an advanced understanding of the location of US states, major cities and landmarks, weather patterns, regional\n"
"economies and demographic patterns, as well as the relationships among these, compared with their understanding of these relationships\n"
"for other countries. In other words, their mental model of the United States is more complex compared with their mental model of other\n"
"countries."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:90
msgid "We can distinguish between a *novice* and a *competent\n"
"practitioner* for a given domain based on the complexity of their mental models."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:93
# unordered list
msgid "*     A *novice* is someone who has not yet built a mental model of the domain."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:94
msgid "They therefore reason by analogy and guesswork,\n"
"borrowing bits and pieces of their mental models of other domains\n"
"which seem superficially similar.\n"
"*     A *competent practitioner* is someone who has a mental model that's good enough for everyday purposes. This model\n"
"does not have to be completely accurate in order to be useful:\n"
"for example, the average driver's mental model of how a car works probably doesn't include\n"
"most of the complexities that a mechanical engineer would be concerned with."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:102
msgid "![Mental Models](../fig/mental_models.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:104
msgid "We will discuss the mental models of experts in more detail in [a later lesson]({{ page.root }}/03-expertise/)."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:106
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Your Mental Models"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:107
msgid ">\n"
"> In the Etherpad, write your primary research domain or area of expertise and some aspects of the mental model you use to frame\n"
"> and understand your work. What concepts/facts are included? What types of relationships are included?\n"
">  \n"
"> This discussion should take about 5 minutes."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:114
msgid "One key insight from research on cognitive development is that\n"
"novices, competent practitioners, and experts each need to be taught differently.\n"
"In particular,\n"
"presenting novices with a pile of facts early on is counter-productive,\n"
"because they don't yet have a model or framework to fit those facts into.\n"
"In fact,\n"
"presenting too many facts too soon can actually reinforce\n"
"an incorrect mental model."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:123
msgid "Most learners coming to Carpentries lessons are novices,\n"
"and do not have a strong mental model of the concepts we are teaching.\n"
"Thus, our primary goal is *not*\n"
"to teach the syntax of a particular programming language, but *to help them construct a working mental model*\n"
"so that they have something to attach facts to. In other words, our goal is to teach people *how to think* about programming and data\n"
"management in a way that will allow them to learn more on their own or understand what they might find online."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:130
# header
msgid "### The Importance of Going Slowly"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:132
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> If someone feels it's too slow, they'll be a bit bored. If they feel it's too fast, they'll never come back to programming."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:133
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> — Kunal Marwaha, SWC instructor"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:134
#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:114
#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:55
# SC/DC Template label
msgid "{: .quotation}"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:136
msgid "If our goal is to help novices construct an accurate and useful mental model of a new intellectual domain,\n"
"this will impact our teaching. For example, we principally want to help learners\n"
"form the right categories and make connections among concepts.  We *don't*\n"
"want to overload them with a slew of unrelated facts, as this will be confusing."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:141
msgid "An important practical implication of this latter point is the pace at which we teach.  \n"
"In the first main episode of Software Carpentry's [lesson on the Unix shell][swc-shell-novice],\n"
"which covers \"Navigating Files and Directories\", there are only four \"commands\"\n"
"for 40 minutes of teaching. Ten minutes per command may seem glacially slow,\n"
"but that episodes's real purpose is to teach learners about paths; later on,\n"
"they will learn about history, wildcards, pipes and filters,\n"
"command-line arguments, redirection,\n"
"and all the other big ideas on which the shell depends,\n"
"and without which people cannot understand how to use commands."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:151
msgid "That mental model of the shell also includes things like:"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:153
# unordered list
msgid "*   Anything you repeat manually, you'll eventually get wrong"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:154
msgid "    (so let the computer repeat things for you by using tab completion\n"
"    and the `history` command).\n"
"*   Lots of little tools, combined as needed, are more productive than\n"
"    a handful of programs.\n"
"    (This motivates the pipe-and-filter model.)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:160
msgid "These two examples illustrate something else as well.\n"
"Learning consists of more than \"just\" building mental models\n"
"and adding information to them;\n"
"creating linkages between concepts and facts is at least as important.\n"
"Telling people that they shouldn't repeat things,\n"
"and that they should try to think in terms of little pieces loosely joined,\n"
"both set the stage for discussing functions.\n"
"Explicitly referring back to pipes and filters in the shell when introducing functions\n"
"helps solidify both ideas."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:170
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Meeting Learners Where They Are"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:171
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> One of the strengths of Carpentry workshops is that we meet learners where they're at. Carpentry instructors"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:172
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> strive to help learners"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:173
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> progress from whatever starting point they happen to be at, without making anyone"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:174
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> feel inferior about their current practices or skillsets. We do this in part by teaching relevant and useful skills"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:175
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> building an inclusive learning environment, and continually getting (and paying attention to!) feedback"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:176
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
