#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:179
# header
msgid "## How \"Knowledge\" Gets in the Way"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:181
msgid "Besides going slowly, what else can we do to facilitate the formation of\n"
"sufficiently accurate mental models? One important action is to address the\n"
"misconceptions of broken mental models."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:185
msgid "Mental models are hardly ever built from scratch. Every learner comes to a topic\n"
"with some amount of information, ideas and opinions about the topic. This is true even\n"
"in the case where a learner can't articulate their prior knowledge and beliefs.  "
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:189
msgid "In many cases, this prior knowledge is incomplete or inaccurate. Inaccurate beliefs can be termed \"misconceptions\" and\n"
"can impede learning by making it more difficult for learners to incorporate new, correct information into their mental\n"
"models.\n"
"Correcting learners' misconceptions is at least as important as presenting them with correct information.\n"
"Broadly speaking, misconceptions fall into three categories:"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:195
# unordered list
msgid "*   Simple *factual errors*, such as believing that Vancouver is the capital of British Columbia."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:196
msgid "    These are the easiest to correct.\n"
"*   *Broken models*, such as believing that motion and acceleration must be in the same direction.\n"
"    We can address these by having learners reason through examples to see contradictions.\n"
"*   *Fundamental beliefs*,\n"
"    such as \"the world is only a few thousand years old\"\n"
"    or \"human beings cannot affect the planet's climate\".\n"
"    These beliefs are deeply connected to the learner's social identity\n"
"    and are the hardest to change."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:205
msgid "Since the Carpentries workshops are focused on novices, and the building of\n"
"strong mental models, we're most interested in the middle category of misconceptions.\n"
"While teaching, we want to expose learners' broken models so that we can help them build better ones."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:209
# header
msgid "## Identifying and Correcting Misconceptions"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:211
msgid "How do we expose misconceptions, especially as they pertain to broken models? How\n"
"can we, in-class, know whether the learners already understand this topic\n"
"(so that the class can move on),\n"
"and if not,\n"
"what misconceptions and gaps in their knowledge we should address."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:217
msgid "To be effective, instructors need feedback on their learners' progress,\n"
"and insight into their learners' mental models.\n"
"This feedback comes through what we call *formative assessments* (in contrast\n"
"  to *summative assessment*)."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:222
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Summative Assessment"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:223
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> *Summative assessment* is used"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:224
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> to judge whether a learner has reached an acceptable level of competence."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:225
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> Learners either \"pass\" or \"fail\" a summative assessment."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:226
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> One example is a driving exam,"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:227
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> which tells the rest of society whether someone can safely be allowed on the road. Most assessment done in university"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:228
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> courses is summative, and is used to assign course grades."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:231
msgid "*Formative assessment* takes place during teaching and learning. It sounds like\n"
"a fancy term, but it can be used to describe any interaction or activity\n"
"that provides feedback to both instructors and learners about learners' level of understanding of the\n"
"material. For learners, this feedback can help focus their study efforts. For instructors, it allows them to refocus\n"
"their instruction to respond to challenges that learners are facing.  "
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:237
msgid "Learners don't \"pass\" or \"fail\" formative assessments; they are simply a feedback mechanism.\n"
"For example, a music teacher might ask a learner to play a scale very slowly\n"
"in order to see whether they are breathing correctly,\n"
"and if not, what they should change."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:242
msgid "Formative assessment is most useful when it happens frequently (we'll talk about how frequently later) and when the\n"
"results are easily interpretable by the learner and instructor."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:245
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Repetition vs. Reflective Practice"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:246
msgid ">\n"
"> The idea that ten thousand hours of practice will make someone an expert in some field\n"
"> is widely known,\n"
"> but reality is much more complex.\n"
"> Practice is not doing the same thing over and over again:\n"
"> practice is doing similar but subtly different things,\n"
"> getting feedback,\n"
"> and then changing behavior in response to that feedback to get cumulatively better.\n"
"> Doing the same thing over and over again is much more likely to solidify bad habits than perfect performance.\n"
"> This is why we emphasize practice and feedback for learners at our workshops and for trainees in our\n"
"> instructor training program."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:259
# header
msgid "## Formative Assessments Come in Many Forms"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:261
msgid "There are many types of formative assessment, and each have their advantages and disadvantages."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:263
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Formative Assessments"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:264
msgid ">\n"
"> Based on your previous educational experience (or even this training so far!)\n"
"> what types of formative assessments do you know about?\n"
">\n"
"> Write your answers in the etherpad; or go around and have each person in the group name one."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:271
msgid "One example of formative assessment that we would like to highlight is\n"
"the multiple choice question (MCQ).\n"
"When designed well,\n"
"these can do much more than just measure how much someone knows.\n"
"For example,\n"
"suppose we are teaching children multi-digit addition.\n"
"A well-designed MCQ would be:"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:279
# code block
msgid "~~~\n"
"Q: what is 27 + 15 ?\n"
"a) 42\n"
"b) 32\n"
"c) 312\n"
"d) 33\n"
"~~~"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:286
#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:142
# SC/DC Template label
msgid "{: .source}"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:288
msgid "The correct answer is 42,\n"
"but each of the other answers provides valuable insight."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:291
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Identify the Misconceptions"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:292
msgid ">\n"
"> Choose one wrong answer and write in the Etherpad what the misconception is associated with that wrong answer.\n"
"> This discussion should take about 10 minutes.\n"
">\n"
">> ## Solution\n"
">>\n"
">> *   If the child answers 32, they are throwing away the carry completely.\n"
">> *   If they answer 312, they know that they can't just discard the carried '1',\n"
">>     but doesn't understand that it's actually a ten\n"
">>     and needs to be added into the next column.\n"
">>     In other words,\n"
">>     they are treating each column of numbers as unconnected to its neighbors.\n"
">> *   If they answer 33 then they know they have to carry the 1,\n"
">>     but are carrying it back into the same column it came from."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:306
#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:342
#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:402
#: instructor-training/_episodes/03-expertise.md:197
#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:106
#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:80
#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:110
#: instructor-training/_episodes/18-management.md:221
#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:314
#: instructor-training/_episodes/24-practices.md:37
# SC/DC Template label
msgid "> {: .solution}"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:309
msgid "Each of these incorrect answers is a *plausible distractor* with *diagnostic power*.\n"
"\"Plausible\" means that it looks like it could be right:\n"
"instructors will often put supposedly-silly answers like \"a fish!\" on MCQs,\n"
"but (a) they don't provide any insight\n"
"and (b) learners actually don't find them funny.\n"
"\"Diagnostic power\" means that each of the distractors helps the instructor figure out\n"
"what concepts learners are having difficulty with.  "
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:317
msgid "Formative assessments are most powerful when an instructor modifies their instruction depending on the\n"
"results of the assessment. An instructor may learn they need to change their pace or review a particular concept.\n"
"Knowing how to respond to the results of a formative assessment is a skill that you will develop over time."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:321
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Handling Outcomes"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:322
msgid ">\n"
"> Formative assessments allow us as instructors to adapt our instruction to our audience.\n"
"> What should we do as instructors if the class chooses:\n"
">\n"
"> 1. mostly one of the wrong answers?  \n"
"> 2. mostly the right answer?  \n"
"> 3. an even spread among options?\n"
">\n"
"> For one of the above, enter your answer in the Etherpad.   \n"
">\n"
"> This discussion should take about 5 minutes.\n"
">\n"
">> ## Solution\n"
">> 1. If the majority of the class votes for a single wrong answer, you should go back\n"
">> and work on correcting that particular misconception.  \n"
">> 2. If most of the class votes\n"
">> for the right answer, it's probably safe to move on.  \n"
">> 3. If answers are pretty evenly\n"
">> split between options, learners are probably guessing randomly and it's a good\n"
">> idea to go back to a point where everyone was on the same page."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:345
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Modeling Novice Mental Models"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:346
msgid ">\n"
"> Take 10 minutes to create a multiple choice question related to a topic you intend to teach.\n"
"> Type it into the Etherpad\n"
"> and explain the diagnostic power of each its distractors,\n"
"> i.e., what misconception is each distractor meant to identify?"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:353
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## A Note on MCQ Design"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:354
msgid ">\n"
"> *   A good MCQ tests for conceptual misunderstanding rather than simple factual knowledge.\n"
">     If you are having a hard time coming up with diagnostic distractors,\n"
">     then either you need to think more about your learners' mental models,\n"
">     or your question simply isn't a good starting point for an MCQ.\n"
"> *   When you are trying to come up with distractors,\n"
">     think about questions that learners asked or problems they had\n"
">     the last time you taught this subject.\n"
">     If you haven't taught it before,\n"
">     think about your own misconceptions\n"
">     or ask colleagues about their experiences."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:367
msgid "Designing an MCQ with plausible distractors is useful\n"
"even if it is never used in class\n"
"because it forces the instructor to think about the learners' mental models\n"
"and how they might be broken---in short,\n"
"to put themselves into the learners' heads\n"
"and see the topic from their point of view."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:374
msgid "There are many types of formative assessments other than MCQs. One (non-exhaustive) list\n"
"to supplement the earlier exercise\n"
"can be found in the [Edutopia assessment group](https://www.edutopia.org/groups/assessment/250941)."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:378
# header
msgid "## Formative Assessments Should Be Frequent"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:380
msgid "Instructors should use a formative assessment ideally every 5 minutes and\n"
"at least every 10-15 minutes\n"
"in order to make sure that the class is actually learning.\n"
"Since the average attention span is usually only this long,\n"
"formative assessments also help break up instructional time\n"
"and re-focus attention.\n"
"Formative assessments can also be used preemptively:\n"
"if you start a class with a question and everyone can answer it correctly,\n"
"then you can safely skip the part of the lecture\n"
"in which you were going to explain something that your learners already know."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:391
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## How Many?"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:392
msgid ">\n"
"> The Carpentries use formative assessments often. How many have we done since the start of this\n"
"> workshop? Put your guess in the Etherpad along with one example and the purpose that assessment served.  \n"
">\n"
"> This discussion should take about 5 minutes.\n"
">\n"
">> ## Solution\n"
">> This will depend on the event they are attending. Most attendees will guess low.\n"
">> The purpose of this exercise is to emphasize the importance of frequent formative\n"
">> assessments and that an individual assessment doesn't have to take a lot of time."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:405
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## A Corollary Regarding Novices"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:406
msgid ">\n"
"> Learners are commonly _far_ too satisfied to not understand key points\n"
"> and remain confused.  If learners remain confused, they are far less likely\n"
"> to adopt our \"good enough\" practices at the conclusion of the workshop.\n"
"> Encourage helpers to support confused learners as far as possible within\n"
"> the flow of the workshop."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:414
# header
msgid "## Optional exercises"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:416
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Confronting the Contradiction"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:417
msgid ">\n"
"> Describe a misconception you have encountered in your own learning or teaching\n"
"> and how to get learners to confront it."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/02-practice-learning.md:422
msgid "[swc-shell-novice]: http://swcarpentry.github.io/shell-novice/\n"
"[wikipedia-dreyfus-skill]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dreyfus_model_of_skill_acquisition"
