#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:23
# header
msgid "## Types of Memory"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:25
msgid "Learning involves memory. For our purposes, human memory can be divided into two different\n"
"layers.\n"
"The first is called *long-term*.\n"
"It is where we store  persistent information like our passwords and our home address.\n"
"It is essentially unbounded\n"
"(barring injury or disease, we will die before it fills up)\n"
"but it is slow to access."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:33
msgid "Our second layer of memory is called *short-term*. This is the\n"
"type of memory you use to actively think about things and is often called working memory. It is much faster, but also much\n"
"smaller: in 1956, George Miller estimated that the average adult's short-term memory could hold\n"
"[7±2 items][wikipedia-7] for a few seconds before things started to drop out.\n"
"This is [why phone numbers are typically 7 or 8 digits long][phone-nums]:\n"
"back when phones had dials instead of keypads,\n"
"that was the longest sequence of numbers most adults could remember accurately\n"
"for as long as it took the dial to go around and around."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:42
msgid "More recent research suggests that short-term memory is actually even smaller than this.\n"
"Regardless of its exact size, which may differ across people and contexts, we know that\n"
"short-term memory is limited. This has important implications for teaching. If we present\n"
"our learners with large amounts of information, without giving them the opportunity to\n"
"practice using it (and thereby transfer it into long-term memory), they won't retain\n"
"the material as well as if we present small amounts of information interspersed with\n"
"practice opportunities. This is yet another reason why going slowly and using\n"
"frequent formative assessment is important."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:51
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Test Your Working Memory (5 min)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:52
msgid ">\n"
"> [This website][memory-test] implements a short test of working memory.  \n"
">\n"
"> Take 5 minutes to complete the exercise. What was your score? Write your answer\n"
"> in the Etherpad."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:59
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Test Your Working Memory - Analog version (5 min)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:60
msgid ">\n"
"> Read the following list and try to memorize the items in it:\n"
">\n"
"> cat, apple, ball, tree, square, head, house, door, box, car, king,\n"
"> hammer, milk, fish, book, tape, arrow, flower, key, shoe\n"
">\n"
"> Without looking at the list again, write down as many words from the list as\n"
"> you can. How many did you remember? Write your answer in the Etherpad."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:70
msgid "Most people will have found they only remember 5-7 words. Don't worry if you\n"
"remembered fewer - many factors can affect short-term memory in different situations.\n"
"Fortunately, there are techniques that we can use to improve our effective short-term memory.\n"
"We'll illustrate one of these techniques and then describe how this is applicable to our\n"
"workshops.  "
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:76
# header
msgid "## Strategies For Memory Management"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:78
msgid "Our role as instructors, therefore, is to help our learners by not flooding their\n"
"short term memory with too much information, partially by providing strategies\n"
"and exercises to help them form the connections that will move concepts into\n"
"long-term memory. What are some tools for doing this?"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:83
# header
msgid "### Chunking"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:85
msgid "One is by explicitly forming connections or groupings.  \n"
"Our minds can store larger numbers of facts in short-term memory by creating *chunks*, or\n"
"relationships among separate items, causing them to be remembered as a single item.\n"
"For example, most of us will remember a word we read as a single item (\"cat\"), rather\n"
"than as a sequence of letters (\"c-a-t\").\n"
"Similarly, the pattern made by five spots on cards or die is remembered as a whole\n"
"rather than as five separate pieces of information."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:93
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Improving Short-term Memory with Chunking"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:94
msgid ">\n"
"> Repeat the memory exercise you did earlier, but this time,\n"
"> try to form short stories or phrases, or a visual image, from the words you see.\n"
">\n"
"> Write the number of words you remembered in the Etherpad.\n"
"> How does this compare with your first attempt?"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:102
msgid "Storing words in groups reduces the number of effective\n"
"items in your short-term memory, allowing you to keep\n"
"more information in your head at once. This is one reason\n"
"why helping our learners to see the connections among\n"
"the concepts we are teaching is so important.  "
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:108
# header
msgid "### Active Learning Through Formative Assessment"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:110
msgid "Formative assessment is a key component in helping learners solidify their understanding\n"
"and transfer ideas from short-term memory into long-term memory. It's important\n"
"to use formative assessments frequently to help learners transition new concepts\n"
"into their long-term memory, before their short-term memory fills up. It can\n"
"be helpful to use pedagogical planning tools to identify the number of concepts\n"
"that are being introduced in a lesson and plan where to include formative\n"
"assessments."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:118
# header
msgid "### Limit concepts"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/05-memory.md:120
msgid "In the same vein as \"going slowly,\" it's important to limit the number of\n"
"concepts introduced in a lesson; no matter how many exercises or formative\n"
"assessments you do, you can't overcome the limit of items that can be\n"
"shored in short-term memory."
msgstr ""

