"> consisting of  `grep`, `sort`, `head`, and `uniq` to explore biological sequence data.\n"
"> This emphasizes how they can apply what they learned with haikus to real bioinformatics research problems.\""
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:156
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Brainstorming Motivational Strategies"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:157
msgid ">\n"
"> *Think* back to a computational (or other) course you took in the past, and\n"
"> identify one thing the instructor did that motivated you.\n"
"> *Pair* up with your neighbor and discuss what motivated you.\n"
"> *Share* the motivational story in the Etherpad.\n"
">\n"
"> This exercise should take about 5 minutes."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:166
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Not Just Learners"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:167
msgid ">\n"
"> What's missing from this list is strategies to motivate the *instructor*.\n"
"> As we said in the introduction,\n"
"> learners respond to an instructor's enthusiasm,\n"
"> and instructors need to care about a topic in order to keep teaching it,\n"
"> particularly when they are volunteers."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:175
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Why Do You Teach? (Optional)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:176
msgid ">\n"
"> We all have a different motivation for teaching, and that is a really good thing!\n"
"> The Carpentries want instructors with diverse backgrounds because you each bring something\n"
"> unique to our community.\n"
">\n"
