#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:187
# header
msgid "## How Not to Demotivate Your Learners"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:189
msgid "Motivation can go both ways. Besides using strategies to motivate learners,\n"
"one of our additional challenges as instructors\n"
"is to not **demotivate** participants through our words or actions. None of us goes into\n"
"a workshop with the intention of creating a hostile environment or making the learners\n"
"hate the tools we're teaching, but we can all accidentally do just that if we don't\n"
"pay attention to what we say and how we interact with our learners. We'll discuss some\n"
"common demotivators and help you develop strategies for avoiding them."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:197
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Brainstorming Demotivational Experiences"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:198
msgid ">\n"
"> *Think* back to a time when you were demotivated as a student (or when you demotivated a student).\n"
"> *Pair* up with your neighbor and discuss what could have been done differently in the situation to make it not demotivating.\n"
"> *Share* your story in the Etherpad.\n"
">\n"
"> If time, what themes do you see among the stories?  What are positive actions you could take to avoid these?\n"
">\n"
"> This exercise should take about 5 minutes."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:208
# header
msgid "### Things You Shouldn't Do in a Workshop"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:210
# unordered list
msgid "*   Tell learners they are rubbish because they use Excel and/or Word,"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:211
msgid "    don't modularize their code, etc.\n"
"*   Say negative things about Windows and praise Linux, e.g., say that\n"
"    the former is for amateurs.\n"
"*   Criticize GUI applications (and by implication their users) and\n"
"    describe command-line tools as the One True Way.\n"
"*   Talk contemptuously or with scorn about any tool. Regardless of\n"
"    its shortcomings, many of your learners may be using that tool.\n"
"    Convincing someone to change their practices is much harder when\n"
"    they think you disdain them.\n"
"*   Dive into complex or detailed technical discussion with the one or\n"
"    two people in the audience who clearly don't actually need to be\n"
"    there.\n"
"*   Pretend to know more than you do.  People will actually trust you\n"
"    more if you are frank about the limitations of your knowledge, and\n"
"    will be more likely to ask questions and seek help.\n"
"*   Use the J word (\"just\") or other demotivating words we talked about in a\n"
"    [previous lesson]({{ page.root }}/03-expertise/). These signal to the learner that\n"
"    the instructor thinks their problem is trivial\n"
"    and by extension that they therefore must be stupid\n"
"    for not being able to figure it out.\n"
"*   Take over the learner's keyboard. It is rarely a good idea to type anything for your learners.\n"
"    Doing so can be demotivating for the learner (as it implies you don't think they can do it themselves or\n"
"    that you don't want to wait for them). It also wastes a valuable opportunity for your learner to develop muscle memory and other\n"
"    skills that are essential for independent work.\n"
"*  Feign surprise. Saying things like \"I can't believe you don't know X\"\n"
"    or \"You've never heard of Y?\" signals to the learner that they do not have\n"
"    some required pre-knowledge of the material you are teaching, that they don't belong at the workshop,\n"
"    and it may prevent them from asking questions in\n"
"    the future. (For more on this see the Recurse Center's [Social Rules][recurse-social-rules])."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:241
msgid "It can be difficult to avoid these demotivators entirely. Some people are so used to\n"
"making fun of Windows-users with their friends, or talking about how terrible Excel is\n"
"that they initially fail to realize they're doing it while teaching. Teaching yourself\n"
"to avoid these types of comments takes practice, but is well worth the effort. No one\n"
"likes to be made fun of, and talking badly about people who use GUIs, or who aren't\n"
"writing their thesis in LaTeX is unlikely to make them excited about learning your\n"
"favorite scripting language."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:249
# header
msgid "## Systemic and Psychological Demotivators"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:251
msgid "As instructors, we can learn to avoid talking disparagingly about our learners' choice\n"
"of text editors and levels of technical knowledge. There are other factors, however, that contribute to demotivation,\n"
"some of which are either systemic, or built into our psychological makeup as human beings. We can't\n"
"always control these demotivators - often they come from outside classrom - but we can\n"
"be aware of them, and take certain actions to lessen their impact by thinking carefully about\n"
"the language that we use and how we interact with our learners."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:258
# header
msgid "### Stereotype Threat"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:259
msgid "One major psychological demotivator is *stereotype threat*. Reminding people of negative stereotypes,\n"
"even in subtle ways, can make them anxious about the risk of confirming those stereotypes, in turn reducing\n"
"their performance. This is called *[stereotype threat][wikipedia-stereotype-threat]*,\n"
"and the clearest examples in computing are gender-related. Depending on whose numbers you trust,\n"
"only 12-18% of programmers are women, and those figures have actually been getting worse over the last 20 years.\n"
"There are many reasons for this (see Margolis and Fisher's *[Unlocking the Clubhouse][worldcat-clubhouse]*\n"
"and Margolis's *[Stuck in the Shallow End][worldcat-shallow-end]*). Steele's *[Whistling Vivaldi][worldcat-whistling-vivaldi]*\n"
"summarizes what we know about stereotype threat in general and presents some strategies for mitigating it in\n"
"the classroom."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:269
msgid "While there's lots of evidence that unwelcoming climates demotivate members of under-represented groups,\n"
"it's not clear that stereotype threat is the underlying mechanism. Part of the problem is that\n"
"[the term has been used in many ways][shapiro-neuberg-stereotype-threat].\n"
"Another is that there are [questions about the replicability of key studies][jussim-stereotype-threat].\n"
"What *is* clear is that we need to avoid thinking in terms of a deficit model\n"
"(i.e., we need to change the members of under-represented groups because they have some deficit,\n"
"such as lack of prior experience) and instead use a systems approach\n"
"(i.e., we need to change the system because it produces these disparities). We\n"
"can also not highlight people based on their identity with a minority group; for\n"
"example, it's not a good idea to say something like \"I'm so glad you're here because\n"
"we don't get enough women in programming.\" That may sound positive,\n"
"but draws attention to the stereotype that women aren't good at programming."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:282
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Never Learn Alone"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:283
msgid ">\n"
"> One way to support at-risk learners of all kinds is to ask people to sign up for workshops in small teams\n"
"> rather than as individuals when possible.\n"
"> If an entire lab group comes,\n"
"> or if attendees are drawn from the same (or closely-related) disciplines,\n"
"> everyone in the room will know in advance\n"
"> that they will be with at least a few people they trust,\n"
"> which increases the chances of them actually coming.\n"
"> Furthermore,\n"
"> if people attend a workshop with their labmates, it's more likely they will\n"
"> work together to implement what they've learned after the workshop has ended."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:297
# header
msgid "### Impostor Syndrome"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:299
msgid "Another major psychological demotivator is *[impostor syndrome][wikipedia-impostor-syndrome]*.\n"
"Imposter syndrome is the belief that one is not good enough for a job or position,\n"
"and that one's achievements are due to luck rather than talent or skill.\n"
"This is also accompanied by the fear of being \"found out\"."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:304
msgid "![XKCD's take on imposter syndrome](https://imgs.xkcd.com/comics/impostor_syndrome.png)\n"
"https://xkcd.com/1954/"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:307
msgid "Academic work is frequently undertaken alone or in small groups but the results are shared and\n"
"criticized publicly. In addition,\n"
"we rarely see the struggles of others, only their finished work, which can feed the belief that everyone\n"
"else finds it easy. Women and minority groups, who already feel additional pressure to prove themselves in\n"
"some settings, [may be particularly affected][high-achieving-women]."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:313
msgid "Two ways of dealing with your own impostor syndrome are:"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:315
# ordered list
msgid "1.  Ask for feedback from someone you respect and trust."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:316
msgid "    Ask them for their honest thoughts on your strengths and achievements,\n"
"    and commit to believing them.\n"
"2.  Look for role models.\n"
"    Who do you know who presents as confident and capable?\n"
"    Think about how they conduct themselves.\n"
"    What lessons can you learn from them?\n"
"    What habits can you borrow?\n"
"    (Remember, they quite possibly also feel as if they are making it up as they go.)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:325
msgid "As an instructor,\n"
"you can help people with their impostor syndrome by\n"
"sharing stories of mistakes that you have made or things you struggled to learn.\n"
"This reassures the class that it's OK to find topics difficult.\n"
"Being open with the group makes it easier to build trust and make learners confident to ask questions.\n"
"(Live coding is great for this:\n"
"typos let the class see you're not superhuman.)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:333
msgid "You can also emphasize that you want questions:\n"
"you are not succeeding as a teacher if no one can follow your class,\n"
"so you're asking learners to help you learn and improve.\n"
"Remember,\n"
"it's much more important to *be* smart than to *look* smart."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:339
msgid "The Ada Initiative has\n"
"[some excellent resources][ada-initiative-resources]\n"
"for teaching about and dealing with imposter syndrome."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:343
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Overcoming Imposter Syndrome (Optional)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:344
msgid ">\n"
"> Think of a time when learning something was difficult for you, or\n"
"> you made a mistake that seemed silly or embarrassing. Is that task still hard for you?\n"
"> In the Etherpad, describe how you might use this as a motivational story to help your learners\n"
"> overcome their own imposter syndrome.\n"
">\n"
"> This exercise should take about 5 minutes."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:353
# header
msgid "### Accessibility Issues"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:355
msgid "Not providing equal access to lessons and exercises\n"
"is about as demotivating as it gets.\n"
"If you look at [our old lesson on Python][swc-python-v4],\n"
"for example,\n"
"you'll find that the text beside the slides includes all of the narration---but\n"
"none of the Python source code.\n"
"Someone using a [screen reader][wikipedia-screen-reader]\n"
"would therefore be able to hear what was being said about the program,\n"
"but wouldn't know what the program actually was."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:365
msgid "While it may not be possible to accommodate everyone's needs,\n"
"it *is* possible to get a good working structure in place\n"
"without any knowledge of what specific disabilities people might have.\n"
"Having at least some accommodations prepared also makes it clear that\n"
"hosts and instructors care enough to have thought about problems in advance,\n"
"and that any additional concerns are likely to be addressed."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:372
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## It Helps Everyone"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:373
msgid ">\n"
"> [Curb cuts][wikipedia-curb-cuts]\n"
"> (the small sloped ramps joining a sidewalk to the street)\n"
"> were originally created to make it easier for wheelchair users to move around,\n"
"> but proved to be equally helpful to people with strollers and grocery carts.\n"
"> Similarly,\n"
"> steps taken to make lessons more accessible to people with various disabilities\n"
"> also help everyone else.\n"
"> Proper captioning of images,\n"
"> for example,\n"
"> benefits people with no or limited vision by giving screen readers something to say:\n"
"> but it also makes the images more findable\n"
"> by exposing their content to search engines."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:388
msgid "The first step is to know what you need to do. There are a number of good resources for learning\n"
"about accessibility."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:391
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Learning about Accessibility"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:392
msgid ">\n"
"> The [UK Home Office](https://hodigital.blog.gov.uk/category/accessibility/) has put together a set of posters of dos and don'ts for making\n"
"> visual and web-based materials more accessible for different populations. Take a look at one of\n"
"> [these posters](https://github.com/UKHomeOffice/posters/blob/master/accessibility/dos-donts/posters_en-UK/accessibility-posters-set.pdf) and\n"
"> put one thing you've learned in the Etherpad.\n"
">\n"
"> Note: There are [translations](https://github.com/UKHomeOffice/posters/tree/master/accessibility)\n"
"> available in a number of languages, including Dutch, French, Spanish, Swedish, Portuguese, German, and\n"
"> Chinese.\n"
">\n"
"> This exercise should take about 5 minutes."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:405
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Accessibility and PDFs"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:406
msgid ">\n"
"> The posters above are in PDF format - which itself can sometimes be inaccessible to people\n"
"> who use screen readers. If you know of a similar resource describing accessibility guidelines\n"
"> that would be more accessible than what's linked above, open an issue on our instructor\n"
"> training curriculum respoistory here: https://github.com/carpentries/instructor-training/issues"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:413
msgid "The [W3C Accessibility Initiative's checklist for presentations][w3c-accessible]\n"
"is a good starting point focused primarily on assisting the visually impaired,\n"
"while Liz Henry's blog post about\n"
"[accessibility at conferences][conference-accessibility]\n"
"has a good checklist for people with mobility issues,\n"
"and this [interview with Chad Taylor][deaf-accessibility]\n"
"is a good introduction to issues faced by those with no or limited hearing."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:421
msgid "The second is to know how well you're doing.\n"
"For example,\n"
"sites like [WebAIM][webaim] allow you to check\n"
"how accessible your online materials are to users with no or limited vision."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:426
msgid "The third,\n"
"and most important,\n"
"is to *involve people with disabilities in decision-making*.\n"
"Our mailing lists are a good place to ask for advice,\n"
"and updates to [our accessibility checklist](https://docs.carpentries.org/topic_folders/hosts_instructors/workshop_needs.html#accessibility)\n"
"are always welcome."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:434
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## What Happens When Accessibility is an Issue? (Optional)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:435
msgid ">\n"
"> Think of a time when you've been affected by, or noticed someone else\n"
"> being affected by issues with accessibility. This may have been at a\n"
"> conference you attended where the elevator was out of service, or maybe\n"
"> a class you were taking relied on audio delivery of content. Describe what happened,\n"
"> how it impacted your (or someone else's) ability to be involved and what could\n"
"> have been done to provide better accessibility in this case.\n"
">\n"
"> This exercise should take about 5 minutes."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:446
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Every Little Bit Counts"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:447
msgid ">\n"
"> Looking at people who work with disability and accessibility, it's\n"
"> easy to be overwhelmed by all the different ways we could make\n"
"> instruction more accessible.  *Don't panic.*  Instead:\n"
">\n"
"> *   *Don't do everything at once.*\n"
">     We don't ask learners in our workshops to adopt all our best practices or tools in one go,\n"
">     but instead to work things in gradually at whatever rate they can manage.\n"
">     Similarly, try to build in accessibility habits when preparing for workshops\n"
">     by adding something new each time.\n"
"> *   *Do the easy things first.*\n"
">     There are plenty of ways to make workshops more accessible\n"
">     that are both easy and don't create extra cognitive load for anyone:\n"
">     font choices, general text size,\n"
">     checking in advance that your room is accessible via an elevator or ramp, etc."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:464
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Accessibility Testing"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:465
msgid ">\n"
"> Find the nearest public transportation drop-off point to your building\n"
"> and walk from there to your office and then to the nearest washroom,\n"
"> making notes about things you think would be difficult for a wheelchair user.\n"
"> Now borrow a wheelchair and repeat the journey.\n"
"> How complete was your list of challenges?\n"
"> And did you notice that the first sentence in this challenge\n"
"> assumed you could walk?"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:475
# header
msgid "### Inclusivity"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:477
msgid "*Inclusivity* is a policy of including people who might otherwise be excluded or marginalized.\n"
"In computing, it means making a positive effort to be more welcoming to women,\n"
"people of color, people with various sexual orientations,\n"
"the elderly, people with physical disabilities, the formerly incarcerated,\n"
"the economically disadvantaged, and everyone else who doesn't fit Silicon Valley's white/Asian male demographic.\n"
"Lee's paper\n"
"\"[What can I do today to create a more inclusive community in CS?]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/lee-create-inclusive-community-2015.pdf)\"\n"
"is a brief, practical guide with references to the research literature.\n"
"These help learners who belong to one or more marginalized or excluded groups,\n"
"but help motivate everyone else as well."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:488
msgid "Many of these can be applied to our workshops,\n"
"such as:"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:491
# unordered list
msgid "*   asking learners to email you before the workshop"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:492
msgid "    to explain how they believe the training could help them achieve their goals;\n"
"*   reviewing notes to make sure they are free from gendered pronouns,\n"
"    that they include culturally diverse names,\n"
"    etc.;\n"
"*   emphasizing that what matters is the rate at which they are learning,\n"
"    not the level of knowledge they had when they started;\n"
"*   encouraging pair programming; and\n"
"*   actively mitigating behavior that some learners may find intimidating,\n"
"    e.g.,\n"
"    use of jargon or \"questions\" that are actually asked to display knowledge."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:503
# header
msgid "## Setting Expectations with the Code of Conduct"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:505
msgid "Finally, a important way that the Carpentries foster an inclusive, respectful\n"
"learning environment is our [Code of Conduct]({{ site.coc }})."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:508
msgid "To make clear what is expected,\n"
"all participants in our workshops are required to conform to the\n"
"[Code of Conduct]({{ site.coc }}).\n"
" Its details are important,\n"
"but the most important thing about it is that it exists:\n"
"knowing that we have rules\n"
"tells people a great deal about our values\n"
"and about what kind of learning experience they can expect."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/08-motivation.md:517
msgid "We will discuss the Code of Conduct in greater detail tomorrow."
msgstr ""

