#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:70
# header
msgid "## Praise Influences Mindset"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:72
msgid "One specific way in which instructors can foster a growth mindset in learners\n"
"is in how we praise. [Carol Dweck's research](http://www.ascd.org/publications/educational-leadership/oct07/vol65/num02/The-Perils-and-Promises-of-Praise.aspx)\n"
"investigated three types of praise: performance-based, effort-based and improvement-based, and looked at how these\n"
"types of praise influence learner's mindsets."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:77
msgid "We're most used to hearing **performance-based praise**. This sort of praise focuses on outcomes and implies that the\n"
"outcome (for example, getting a correct answer) is the most important part of the task. It is often (but not always)\n"
"combined with language that explicitly or implicitly supports the \"intrinsic\" model of competence. For example, \"You\n"
"did a great job! You must be very smart.\""
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:82
msgid "**Effort-based praise** focuses on the learner's hard work. For example, \"You did a good job, you must have worked very hard.\"\n"
"Exposing learners frequently to this type of praise helps them to transition from a fixed mindset to a growth mindset by\n"
"changing their perception of effort. For fixed-mindset people, if something doesn't come easy to you, it means that you\n"
"don't have natural ability and shouldn't bother. People with a growth mindset are much more likely to persevere in the face of challenge\n"
"and accomplish their goals."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:88
msgid "**Improvement-based praise** is related to praise based on effort, but explicitly draws a learner's attention to the progress they've made.\n"
"For example, \"You're doing so much better at this than last time, you must have worked very hard.\" This helps reinforce a growth-mindset by\n"
"highlighting our ability to improve with effort."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:92
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Choosing our Praises"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:93
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> Since we're so used to being praised for our performance, it can be challenging to change the way we praise our learners. Which of these"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:94
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> are examples of performance-based, effort-based, or improvement-based praise?"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:95
msgid ">\n"
"> - I like the way you tried a couple of different strategies to solve that problem.\n"
"> - You're getting really good at that. Keep up the hard work!\n"
"> - You're really talented.\n"
"> - That was a hard problem. You didn't get the right answer, but look at how much you learned trying to solve it!\n"
">\n"
">> ## Solution\n"
">> - Effort-based.\n"
">> - Improvement-based.\n"
">> - Performance-based.\n"
">> - Improvement-based."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:110
# header
msgid "## Errors are Essential to Learning"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:112
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> The typos are the pedagogy."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:113
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> — Emily Jane McTavish"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:116
msgid "Another example of how our beliefs (in this case, our emotions) impact learning\n"
"is in how we think about errors.  One of the barriers to learning is avoidance of making errors. Errors are associated with negative emotions, which leads to learners being\n"
"fearful of making them."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:120
msgid "*Positive error framing* is the process of presenting errors as an integral part of the learning process and using them as teaching opportunities. Error framing encourages learners to understand that making errors provides valuable learning opportunities instead\n"
"of having negative consequences. For example, the [Language Acquisition Made Practical](http://www.worldcat.org/title/language-acquisition-made-practical-field-methods-for-language-learners/oclc/935845446?referer=di&ht=edition) (LAMP)\n"
"system for learning language encourages learners to develop phrases and try them in a variety of social situations with native speakers. By\n"
"being willing to make mistakes, LAMP learners receive useful feedback from native speakers in real-world social situations. Error framing has\n"
"shown to be useful in learning complex tasks such as programming. In one study, Steele-Johnson showed that error framing showed\n"
"[positive effects on metacognition and self-efficacy](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24617273)."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:127
msgid "How can we incorporate error framing into our lessons? We need to reduce the negative emotions associated with errors, instead casting errors\n"
"as a \"[natural part of learning](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/292881989_Enhancing_firm_performance_and_innovativeness_through_error_management_culture)\".\n"
"Sharing experiences of learning from errors can encourage learners to adopt a growth-mindset. Associating improvement-based praise with errors\n"
"can also encourage positive emotions associated with making errors in learning. Finally, the use of\n"
"[participatory live coding]({{ page.root }}/14-live/) as the focus for teaching allows for instructors to model how errors can be positively\n"
"framed and the process for overcoming them."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:134
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Helping Learners Learn From Mistakes (optional)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/09-mindset.md:135
