#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:25
# header
msgid "## Lesson Study: Applying a Growth Mindset to Teaching"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:27
msgid "We've seen that providing opportunities for practice\n"
"and giving useful feedback to learners are essential components in the learning\n"
"process. Learning to teach is no different."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:31
msgid "However, many people assume that teachers are born, not made.  From politicians\n"
"to researchers and teachers themselves, most reformers have designed systems to\n"
"find and promote those who can teach and eliminate those who can't.\n"
"As Elizabeth Green describes in *[Building a Better Teacher][worldcat-babt]*, though,\n"
"that assumption is wrong, which is why educational reforms based on it have repeatedly failed."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:37
msgid "To assume that teaching is an \"inherited\" or innate skill is to take on a fixed\n"
"mindset about teaching. A growth mindset believes that anyone can become a better\n"
"teacher by the same methods we use to learn any subject -- reflective practice.\n"
"More specifically, instructors develop teaching skill\n"
"over time through practice and improve most when given feedback on their performance\n"
"from other instructors who share their pedagogical model."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:44
msgid "We know that teachers can learn how to teach because of research done on\n"
"the Japanese method of jugyokenkyu or \"lesson study.\""
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:47
msgid "In the 1980s and 90s, an educational psychologist named James Stigler observed\n"
"teachers in the US and Japan. In the [OECD's annual rankings][oecd-pisa] of countries' educational\n"
"achievements, Japanese students routinely test near the top in reading, math and science, while\n"
"American students rank at or below average."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:52
msgid "Looking at differences in teaching methods, Stigler found that American teachers met at most once\n"
"a year to exchange ideas about teaching, compared to the weekly or even daily meetings of Japanese\n"
"teachers. During these meetings, teachers in the US described their lessons to each other, but they did\n"
"not observe each others' teaching in practice. In contrast, Japanese teachers regularly conducted lesson study:\n"
"observing each other at work, discussing the lesson afterward, and studying curriculum materials with their\n"
"colleagues."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:59
msgid "The situation is different in many English-language school systems:\n"
"in the US, Canada, the UK, Australia, and elsewhere, where often\n"
"what happens in the classroom stays in the classroom.\n"
"Teachers aren't able to watch each other's lessons on a regular basis,\n"
"so they can't borrow each other's good ideas.\n"
"The result is that *every teacher has to invent teaching on their own*.\n"
"They may get lesson plans and assignments from colleagues,\n"
"the school board,\n"
"a textbook publisher,\n"
"or the Internet,\n"
"but each teacher has to figure out on their own how to combine that with\n"
"the theory they've learned in their educational programs\n"
"to deliver an actual lesson in an actual classroom for actual learners.\n"
"When teachers don't observe each other teaching, the tricks and techniques that each instructor\n"
"has painstakingly incorporated into their practice don't have the opportunity to spread, limiting\n"
"forward momentum on system-wide improvements to teaching."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:76
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Reading It Isn't Enough"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:77
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> Several research studies (in [2007][fincher-warren], [2012][fincher-stories], and [2015][barker-practice]) have shown"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:78
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> that teachers don't adopt instructional practices based on reports about the effectiveness of those practices."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:79
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> Social norms, institutional"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:80
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> culture, and lack of time and support prevent many teachers from moving out of"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:81
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> their accustomed teaching habits. Change in teaching doesn't come about through reading about new teaching practices, but by seeing"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:82
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> these practices in action, practicing them and getting feedback from other instructors."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:85
msgid "Therefore, just like other disciplines (sports and music are two good examples), teachers benefit from closely\n"
"observing the work of others.  The Carpentries pedagogical model supports lesson\n"
"study by providing many opportunities for our instructors\n"
"to learn from each other. In this training workshop, you will have opportunities to practice teaching for one another\n"
"and to give each other feedback.  You'll also have the opportunity to practice in front of an experienced instructor\n"
"as part of your instructor training checkout. In addition, Carpentries instructors always teach in pairs (or more),\n"
"giving you the opportunity to learn by observing and to get feedback from your fellow instructors."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:93
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Giving Feedback"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:94
msgid ">\n"
"> We'll start by observing some examples of teaching and providing some feedback.\n"
">\n"
"> Watch this [example teaching video][bad-teaching-video] as a group\n"
"> and then give feedback on it. Put your feedback in the Etherpad.\n"
"> Organize your feedback along two axes:\n"
"> positive vs. negative\n"
"> and content (what was said) vs. presentation (how it was said).\n"
"> This exercise should take about 10 minutes."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:105
msgid "Now that you've had some practice observing teaching and giving feedback, let's practice with each other."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:107
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Feedback on Yourself"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:108
msgid ">\n"
"> The goal of this exercise is to practice giving and receiving feedback, so don't be\n"
"> overly concerned about creating a perfectly polished presentation.\n"
"> We don't give you a lot of time to prep and the teaching time is short, so embrace\n"
"> the challenge (and improvisation) of the exercise and see what you can learn by\n"
"> watching other people teach, thinking about how to give them feedback, and how it\n"
"> feels to get feedback on your own teaching.\n"
">\n"
"> **Trainings where trainees are co-located:**\n"
"> 1.  Split into groups of three.\n"
"> 2.  Individually, spend 5 minutes preparing to teach a 90-second segment of\n"
">     the lesson episode you chose before the start of the training course. You will not\n"
">     be live coding; you can use a whiteboard or other visual aids if available (but\n"
">     this is not required!). We recommend using this 90 second teaching moment\n"
">     to introduce the topic of your lesson.\n"
"> 3.  Get together with your group and have each person teach their segment to the group,\n"
">     while one person records this (video and audio)\n"
">     using a cell phone or some other handheld device.\n"
">     Keep a strict time limit of 90 seconds per person.\n"
"> 3.  After the first person finishes,\n"
">     rotate roles\n"
">     (they become the videographer,\n"
">     the audience becomes the instructor,\n"
">     the person who was recording becomes the audience)\n"
">     and then rotate roles again.\n"
"> 4.  After everyone in the group of three has finished teaching,\n"
">     watch the videos as a group.\n"
">     Everyone gives feedback on all three videos,\n"
">     i.e., people give feedback on themselves as well as on others.\n"
"> 5.  After everyone has given feedback on all of the videos,\n"
">     return to the main group and put everyone's feedback about you into the Etherpad.\n"
">\n"
"> **Distributed trainings:**\n"
"> Your Trainer will split the group into virtual break-out rooms. Follow the instructions above\n"
"> but do not record each other. Instead, give each person feedback immediately after they finish their\n"
"> turn teaching.\n"
">\n"
"> This exercise should take about 25 minutes."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:148
# header
msgid "## Feedback Is Hard"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:150
msgid "Sometimes it can be hard to receive feedback, especially negative feedback."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:152
msgid "![Feedback Feelings](../fig/deathbulge-jerk.jpg \"Comic from http://www.deathbulge.com/comics/155\")"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:154
msgid "Feedback is most effective when the people involved\n"
"share ground rules and expectations. In Carpentries teaching, we use the 2x2\n"
"paradigm for feedback. Each person giving feedback is expected to provide at least one\n"
"piece of negative and one piece of positive feedback each for content and delivery. This\n"
"helps overcome two common tendencies when giving feedback on teaching: to focus on the content\n"
"(even though delivery is at least as important) and to either provide only negative or\n"
"only positive feedback."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:162
msgid "Here is a list of different\n"
"ways that you can set the stage for receiving or providing feedback\n"
"in a way that facilitates growth."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:166
# unordered list
msgid "*   Initiate feedback as the instructor. It's better to ask for feedback than to receive it unwillingly."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:168
# unordered list
msgid "*   Ask for and give specific feedback. See a great example of this from"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:169
msgid "  this Lunar Baboon comic: ![Giving Good Feedback](../fig/feedback-artwork.jpg \"Comic from http://www.lunarbaboon.com/comics/feedback.html\")"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:171
msgid "  As an instructor one way to get specific feedback is to provide questions that\n"
"  focus the responses.  Writing your own feedback questions allows you to frame\n"
"  feedback in a way that is helpful to you - the questions below\n"
"  reveal what didn't work in your teaching, but read as professional suggestions rather than personal judgments.\n"
"  For example:"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:177
# unordered list
msgid "* \"What is one thing I could have done as an instructor to make this lesson more effective?\""
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:178
# unordered list
msgid "* \"If you could pick one thing from the lesson to go over again, what would it be?\""
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:180
# unordered list
msgid "* Balance positive and negative feedback."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:181
# unordered list
msgid "    * Ask for or give \"compliment sandwiches\" (one positive, one negative, one positive)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:182
# unordered list
msgid "    * Ask for both types of feedback, and give both types."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/11-practice-teaching.md:184
# unordered list
