#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:72
# header
msgid "## Reverse Instructional Design (and Preparation!)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:74
msgid "When sitting down to plan a course or workshop, it might be tempting to dive into reviewing the content, questioning your\n"
"understanding, and anticipating questions that learners might have for you. While it is good to prepare your content, this\n"
"approach can take you down extended rabbit-holes in which you anticipate and research questions that only an expert\n"
"would think to ask, and never get around to thinking about how to get your learners from one point to the next, and how to\n"
"know when they've gotten there.  "
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:80
msgid "This is a problem with curriculum design as well as preparation. When writing curriculum, it is easy to allow *content*\n"
"objectives to distract from *learning* objectives. One way to prevent this is to take a \"reverse\" approach to instruction, as\n"
"advanced in Wiggins and McTighe's *[Understanding by Design](http://www.worldcat.org/title/understanding-by-\n"
"design/oclc/56491025)*, that keeps the focus firmly on learning outcomes. The order of preparation in this case becomes"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:85
# ordered list
msgid "1.  Determine your learning objectives"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:86
# ordered list
msgid "2.  Decide what constitutes evidence that objectives have been met, and design assessments to target that evidence"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:87
# ordered list
msgid "3.  Design instruction: Sort assessments in order of increasing complexity, and write content that connects everything together"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:89
msgid "In the context of preparing for a Carpentries-style workshop, the lesson design has already occurred, and many lessons include\n"
"pre-written exercises to use for assessment. In this context, *reverse instructional design*  principles might be applied as\n"
"follows: 1) review the lesson's learning objectives carefully, thinking about how they will work for your audience, 2) scan\n"
"the lesson to identify promising points to check in with your learners, using formative assessment to verify that objectives have been met, and then 3) review the connecting content in detail to be sure everything works and you have anticipated likely problems and questions."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:95
# header
msgid "## Working With Learning Objectives"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:96
msgid "Once you have an idea of your intended audience, the next step is to think through the goals for your workshop. These goals\n"
"are usually communicated through *learning objectives*."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:99
msgid "The \"learning objectives\" section is an easy thing to pass over when you're preparing to teach. It may seem obvious or\n"
"unnecessary. However, good learning objectives are quite specific about the intended effect of a lesson on its learners. We\n"
"aim to create learning objectives that are specific, accurate, and informative for both learners and instructors."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:103
msgid "[Bloom's Taxonomy](https://cft.vanderbilt.edu/guides-sub-pages/blooms-taxonomy/) is a framework for thinking about learning that breaks progress down into discrete, hierarchical steps.\n"
"While many ideas have come and gone in education, Bloom's has remained a useful tool for educators, in particular because the\n"
"hierarchy seems to be reasonably valid: outcomes at the top of the hierarchy cannot be achieved without mastery of outcomes at\n"
"the bottom. In the long term, everybody wants to be at the top. However, in aiming to meet learners where they are, we also\n"
"need to be mindful about helping them to [\"grow a level,\"](https://software-carpentry.org/blog/2018/03/tractenberg-summary.html) helping them to recognize when they have achieved that growth, and\n"
"guiding them to look ahead to where we might not be able to take them."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:110
msgid "![Bloom's Taxonomy](../fig/Blooms.png)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:112
msgid "Image credit: Vanderbilt University Center for Teaching"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:114
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Evaluate Learning Objectives"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:115
msgid ">\n"
"> Your instructor has posted links to a handful of current Carpentries lessons in the Etherpad.\n"
"> Select one learning objective from one of those lessons,\n"
"> then complete the following steps to evaluate it.\n"
">\n"
"> 1. Identify the learning objective verb. How specifically does this verb describe the desired learner outcome?\n"
"> 2. Where does this verb fit on Bloom's taxonomy? Do you think this is an appropriate level for your learners?\n"
"> 3. In your opinion, does the lesson do an effective job of meeting the stated objective?\n"
"> 4. What would the next level on Bloom's taxonomy look like for your learners? How might you be able to help them think ahead\n"
"> to the next level without attempting to get them there during your workshop?\n"
">\n"
"> This exercise should take about 10 minutes.  "
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:130
# header
msgid "## Using Formative Assessments"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:132
msgid "When assessments are created in a reverse-design setting, their primary purpose is to inform the instructor about whether\n"
"objectives have been met. But, as noted in previous lessons, these assessments are good for everyone! For learners, becoming\n"
"more aware of their progress is motivating and helps to transfer learned content to long-term memory.\n"
"Awareness of the learning process, also known as \"metacognition,\" will also help them to identify appropriate next steps after a workshop has completed."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:137
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Where are your checkpoints?"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:138
msgid ">\n"
"> Have a look at your lesson again. Choose a learning objective, and identify\n"
"> *where* in the lesson that objective should reasonably be achieved. How will\n"
"> you know that that objective has been met for all learners? Will this be clear\n"
"> to them?\n"
">\n"
"> Make a plan for *where* in your lesson you will use different types of\n"
"> formative assessment to help everyone in the room monitor their progress. Keep\n"
"> in mind that formative assessment can take many forms, including multiple\n"
"> choice questions, faded examples, spontaneous questions and calls for sticky\n"
"> notes. Write some notes or thoughts about this process in the Etherpad for\n"
"> discussion.\n"
">\n"
"> This exercise and discussion should take about 10 minutes."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:155
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## You Can't Just Ask"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:156
msgid ">\n"
"> Self-assessments of skill level are usually inaccurate\n"
"> because of the [Dunning-Kruger effect](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dunning%E2%80%93Kruger_effect):\n"
"> the less people know about a subject,\n"
"> the less accurate their estimate of their knowledge is. This is one reason why assessments should be specific, as\n"
"> opposed to asking if everyone understands."
