#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:95
# header
msgid "### 1. Set Positive First Impressions"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:97
msgid "First impressions can be long-lasting. Before you even start teaching, your learners\n"
"will have already made some decisions about you, so it is important to\n"
"understand what those impressions are based on and how to manage them."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:101
msgid "**Your attire.** Research shows that clothing affects the\n"
"judgments people make, including credibility,\n"
"likability, dominance, kindness, and empathy (Raiscot, 1986; Morris et\n"
"al., 1996). More formal attire communicates expertise and confidence.\n"
"Less formal attire communicates approachability. Usually, it is easier\n"
"to relax from a more formal impression into a more relaxed one than the\n"
"other way around. These considerations are likely to be particularly\n"
"relevant for young instructors who are concerned about establishing\n"
"themselves as authoritative."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:111
msgid "**The physical environment**. Learners can make decisions about what\n"
"kind of course yours will be by the way the chairs are arranged. Rows\n"
"signify a more formal environment, while circles or U-shapes imply a\n"
"more informal atmosphere, with higher expectations of learner\n"
"participation."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:117
msgid "**Your use of the few minutes before class.** Greeting the learners as\n"
"they enter the classroom communicates approachability. Frantically\n"
"arriving right on time or late communicates disorganization."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:121
# header
msgid "### 2. Introduce Yourself Effectively"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:123
msgid "Your introduction should be succinct, but make sure to cover certain\n"
"key areas. These questions should help you decide what to say:"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:126
msgid "**What characteristics do you want to convey about yourself?** You probably want the learners to get a sense of your\n"
"qualifications, how formal/informal you want\n"
"to be, and how available you will be to the learners. You want to\n"
"demonstrate that you're qualified, but that you share the same\n"
"challenges as the learners, so you remain accessible."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:132
msgid "**What will you need to say to convey those characteristics?**\n"
"Consider talking about your research and computational interests as\n"
"they relate to the workshop, in order to establish yourself as an\n"
"authority, and to make the workshop more relevant."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:137
msgid "**Why are you teaching a Carpentries workshop?**\n"
"Why are you an instructor? What's motivating you to be there today? One\n"
"reason might be that you took a workshop and saw how valuable these\n"
"skills were in your own work and wanted to share this information with\n"
"others. Convey your enthusiasm for being there."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:143
msgid "**What should you be careful not to say?** Learners do not need to\n"
"know everything about you. In particular, it is not helpful to say\n"
"you've never taught the course before, or that it is your least\n"
"favorite course to teach, or to disclose any irrelevant personal\n"
"information that can undermine you in the eyes of your learners."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:149
# blockquote, which can be cascaded
msgid "> ## Introductions for Everyone"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:150
msgid ">\n"
